══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  SUMMARY , WHAT THIS TELLS US
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

  The 3x4 matrix format is the engine's possible universal transform node.
  The game possibly uses one data structure for everything:
    - HUD elements (life bars, icons, timer)
    - Stage geometry (floor, walls, shadows, background)
    - Character mesh layer (transparency, shader params, T-pose base)
    - Character skeleton (pose bones, cloth/accessory)

  Ryu's full transform hierarchy:
    World position  (0x924707C0)
    ↓
    Mesh/polygon base  (0x92472440)
    ↓
    Skeleton root  (0x92475AC0)
    ↓
    Spine → Hip → Legs → Feet
    Spine → Shoulders → Arms → Hands
    Spine → Neck → Head → Accessories

  The "attach to enemy" descriptions at 0x92472540/0x92472580 are
  possibly the throw mechanic, the attacker's skeleton
  is parented to the defender's transform during the throw animation.

  Transparent/alpha bones control render order or alpha blend params,
  not geometry , zeroing them makes parts invisible, not misplaced.

  The freeze bones are live engine pointers or loop counters embedded
  in the same memory region. They are NOT transform nodes.